# Dashboard System

The Dashboard is the central command center of LexMastery.

It is not a static home screen.

It is a dynamic learning intelligence system.

---

# Product Vision

The Dashboard must:

- Guide daily learning
- Show progress clearly
- Reinforce habits
- Surface AI recommendations
- Reduce decision fatigue

Every element must answer:

"What should I do next?"

---

# Dashboard Philosophy

The Dashboard is:

- Personalized
- Adaptive
- Action-driven
- Minimal but powerful
- AI-assisted

Avoid clutter at all costs.

---

# Architecture

Presentation Layer

↓

DashboardController (Riverpod)

↓

DashboardState

↓

DashboardRepository

↓

Data Sources (API + Local Cache)

---

# State Management

DashboardState must include:

- loading
- error
- empty
- loaded
- refreshing

Data groups:

- Continue Learning
- Recommended Courses
- Daily Goals
- AI Suggestions
- Upcoming Exams
- Streaks
- Recent Activity

---

# Dashboard Widgets

Mandatory widgets:

Continue Learning Card

Daily Study Goal

AI Recommendation Panel

Upcoming Exam Countdown

Learning Streak Tracker

Performance Summary

Recent Activity Feed

---

# Widget Rules

Each widget must:

- Be independently loadable
- Support skeleton loading
- Support offline cache
- Have empty states
- Be reusable in other screens

---

# Data Prioritization

Priority order:

1. Continue Learning
2. Upcoming Exams
3. AI Recommendations
4. Daily Goals
5. Progress Analytics
6. Activity Feed

---

# AI Integration

AI drives dashboard personalization:

- Suggest next lesson
- Adjust difficulty
- Recommend revision
- Predict weak areas

AI suggestions must be explainable.

---

# Navigation Rules

Dashboard is the root after authentication.

From dashboard users can access:

Courses

AI Tutor

Quiz Engine

Study Planner

Profile

Settings

---

# Offline Behaviour

Dashboard must work offline using cached data.

Restrictions:

- AI suggestions disabled offline
- Activity feed uses cached logs
- Progress data remains accessible

---

# Analytics Events

dashboard_view

dashboard_widget_view

dashboard_continue_learning_click

dashboard_ai_suggestion_click

dashboard_exam_click

---

# Performance

Dashboard must load initial shell in <300ms.

Widgets load progressively.

Never block UI on full data fetch.

---

# Error Handling

Each widget handles its own errors.

Dashboard must not fail entirely.

Partial rendering is allowed.

---

# Accessibility

Dashboard must:

- Support screen readers
- Provide labeled widgets
- Maintain logical tab order
- Avoid information overload

---

# Testing Requirements

Unit Tests:

DashboardController logic

Widget data mapping

AI recommendation integration

Widget Tests:

Each dashboard widget

Loading/empty/error states

Integration Tests:

Full dashboard load

Offline mode behavior

Navigation flow

---

# Security Rules

Do not expose sensitive AI data in logs.

User progress data must be encrypted at rest.

---

# Cursor Instructions

When generating dashboard features:

- Always use widget-based architecture
- Always support partial rendering
- Always implement AI-driven recommendations
- Always include offline fallback
- Always include skeleton loading states
- Never make dashboard a static UI